These are your memory: {"type": "action_response", "result": "### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe problem revolves around the limitations of traditional machine learning approaches on tabular data, which heavily depend on model structure, activation functions, and the quality of training data. Manual intervention by domain experts is often required for feature transformation, which is time-consuming and labor-intensive.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n1. **Expansion-Reduction Approaches:** These methods randomly generate features through mathematical transformations and then use feature selection techniques to isolate high-quality features. They are stochastic, lack stability, and do not learn from transformation steps.\n2. **Iterative-Feedback Approaches:** These methods refine the feature space with transformations towards reinforcement learning and evolutionary algorithms. They have shown some success in terms of performance metrics like 1-RAE and F1-score but still have limitations.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- The need for more stable and strategy-learning feature transformation methods.\n- The desire to reduce reliance on manual intervention and expensive supervised feedback.\n- The need for methods that can effectively capture complex feature interactions without extensive human effort.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Hybrid Feature Transformation Framework:**\n   - Combine graph-based methods with reinforcement learning to capture complex feature interactions and learn transformation strategies.\n   - Use historical information from the graph to identify optimal substructures and explore transformations.\n\n2. **Automated Feature Transformation with Large Language Models:**\n   - Integrate large language models (LLMs) to guide feature transformation processes, leveraging their ability to understand and generate complex patterns.\n   - Use LLMs to automate the identification of high-value sub-transformations and generate high-quality feature spaces.\n\n3. **Explainable Feature Transformation:**\n   - Develop methods that not only transform features but also provide explanations for the transformations, enhancing interpretability.\n   - Use techniques like SHAP or LIME to explain the importance and impact of generated features.\n\n4. **Feature Transformation with Multi-Agent Systems:**\n   - Implement multi-agent systems to automate the identification of effective feature subsets, reducing reliance on human effort.\n   - Use agents to explore different feature transformation strategies and select the most effective ones.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe key gaps identified in the literature are the need for more stable, strategy-learning feature transformation methods that reduce reliance on manual intervention and expensive supervised feedback. Potential research ideas include hybrid frameworks combining graph-based methods with reinforcement learning, automated feature transformation using large language models, explainable feature transformation, and feature transformation with multi-agent systems.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nMachine learning on tabular data is highly dependent on manual feature transformation, which is time-consuming and lacks stability. There is a need for automated, strategy-learning methods that can capture complex feature interactions and reduce reliance on human expertise.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we develop an automated feature transformation method that learns transformation strategies, captures complex feature interactions, and reduces reliance on manual intervention?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nSolving this problem will significantly streamline the data preparation phase in machine learning, making it more efficient and accessible. It will also enhance the performance of downstream models by generating high-quality feature spaces. This research will advance the field of machine learning by providing a robust solution to a critical challenge.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nThe challenge lies in developing a method that can learn transformation strategies, capture complex feature interactions, and ensure stability. Naive approaches may fail due to their stochastic nature and lack of strategy learning. Overcoming these challenges requires a combination of advanced machine learning techniques and domain expertise.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious methods have focused on either expansion-reduction or iterative-feedback approaches, which lack stability and strategy learning. The integration of graph-based methods, reinforcement learning, and large language models represents a novel approach that addresses these limitations.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology will combine graph-based methods with reinforcement learning to capture complex feature interactions and learn transformation strategies. We will use historical information from the graph to identify optimal substructures and explore transformations. The expected outcomes include a stable, strategy-learning feature transformation method that reduces reliance on manual intervention and enhances the performance of downstream models. We will evaluate the method on benchmark datasets using metrics like 1-RAE and F1-score."} {"type": "action_response", "result": "To proceed with refining the 5Q format and drafting the full research proposal, I will start by expanding the 5Q format into a structured full research proposal document. Here is the draft:\n\n---\n\n### Full Research Proposal\n\n#### Introduction\nMachine learning (ML) on tabular data is highly dependent on manual feature transformation, which is time-consuming and lacks stability. This research aims to develop an automated feature transformation method that learns transformation strategies, captures complex feature interactions, and reduces reliance on manual intervention. By integrating graph-based methods with reinforcement learning, we propose a novel approach that addresses the limitations of existing methodologies.\n\n#### Literature Review\nTraditional ML approaches on tabular data often rely on manual feature transformation, which is labor-intensive and lacks stability. Expansion-reduction and iterative-feedback approaches have been proposed but suffer from stochastic nature and lack of strategy learning. Recent advancements in graph-based methods, reinforcement learning, and large language models offer promising solutions to these challenges.\n\n#### Methodology\nThe proposed methodology combines graph-based methods with reinforcement learning to capture complex feature interactions and learn transformation strategies. We will use historical information from the graph to identify optimal substructures and explore transformations. The key components of the approach include:\n- **Graph-based Feature Representation:** Utilize graph neural networks to represent features and their interactions.\n- **Reinforcement Learning for Strategy Learning:** Implement reinforcement learning to learn effective feature transformation strategies.\n- **Evaluation Metrics:** Use metrics like 1-RAE and F1-score to evaluate the performance of the proposed method.\n\n#### Expected Outcomes\nThe expected outcomes of this research include:\n- A stable, strategy-learning feature transformation method that reduces reliance on manual intervention.\n- Enhanced performance of downstream models by generating high-quality feature spaces.\n- Improved efficiency and accessibility of the data preparation phase in ML.\n\n#### Conclusion\nThis research aims to advance the field of machine learning by providing a robust solution to the critical challenge of automated feature transformation. By integrating graph-based methods with reinforcement learning, we propose a novel approach that addresses the limitations of existing methodologies and contributes to the development of more efficient and accessible ML systems.\n\n---\n\n### Next Steps\n1. **Peer Review:** Share the draft with peers or mentors for feedback.\n2. **Final Review and Submission:** Conduct a final review to ensure all aspects of the proposal are addressed and prepare it for submission to a relevant conference or journal.\n\nThis draft provides a structured and comprehensive overview of the research proposal. The next step is to seek feedback and make any necessary revisions before final submission."}

