e proposal.\n\n3. **Prepare for Implementation:**\n   - Identify the necessary resources and tools required for the research.\n   - Plan the timeline and milestones for the project.\n\n4. **Write the Final Proposal:**\n   - Based on the feedback and refinement, write the final version of the research proposal.\n   - Ensure that the proposal is well-organized and easy to follow.\n\nHere is a refined version of the research proposal based on the current draft:\n\n---\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nAutomated feature transformation is crucial for improving the performance of machine learning models on tabular data, but existing methods often lack stability, strategy learning, and the ability to reuse high-value sub-transformations.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we develop an automated feature transformation method that is stable, learns from past transformations, and reuses high-value sub-transformations to generate high-quality feature spaces?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nSolving this problem will significantly reduce the reliance on manual intervention by domain experts, improve the performance of machine learning models, and make the feature transformation process more efficient and explainable. This will have broad implications for various fields that rely on machine learning, including urban planning, healthcare, and finance.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nThe challenges include developing a method that can learn from past transformations, reuse high-value sub-transformations, and ensure the stability and explainability of the feature transformation process. Naive approaches may fail due to the stochastic nature of feature generation and the lack of a strategy learning mechanism.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious methods either lack stability and strategy learning (expansion-reduction approaches) or do not effectively reuse high-value sub-transformations (iterative-feedback approaches). There is a need for a hybrid approach that combines the strengths of both methods and incorporates graph-based models and reinforcement learning with memory.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology will involve developing a graph-based feature transformation model that learns from past transformations and reuses high-value sub-transformations. The model will be trained using reinforcement learning with memory and evaluated on various tabular datasets using metrics like 1-RAE and F1-score. The expected outcomes include a more stable, efficient, and explainable feature transformation method that can generate high-quality feature spaces.\n\n---\n\nOnce the proposal is finalized, the next step would be to begin the implementation phase, starting with the development of the graph-based feature transformation model and the training process."}, 'task_results': [{'agent1': 'Result from the model:To proceed with refining the 5Q format and drafting the full research proposal, I will start by expanding the 5Q format into a structured full research proposal document. Here is the draft:\n\n---\n\n### Full Research Proposal\n\n#### Introduction\nMachine learning (ML) on tabular data is highly dependent on manual feature transformation, which is time-consuming and lacks stability. This research aims to develop an automated feature transformation method that learns transformation strategies, captures complex feature interactions, and reduces reliance on manual intervention. By integrating graph-based methods with reinforcement learning, we propose a novel approach that addresses the limitations of existing methodologies.\n\n#### Literature Review\nTraditional ML approaches on tabular data often rely on manual feature transformation, which is labor-intensive and lacks stability. Expansion-reduction and iterative-feedback approaches have been proposed but suffer from stochastic nature and lack of strategy learning. Recent advancements in graph-based methods, reinforcement learning, and large language models offer promising solutions to these challenges.\n\n#### Methodology\nThe proposed methodology combines graph-based methods with reinforcement learning to capture complex feature interactions and learn transformation strategies. We will use historical information from the graph to identify optimal substructures and explore transformations. The key components of the approach include:\n- **Graph-based Feature Representation:** Utilize graph neural networks to represent features and their interactions.\n- **Reinforcement Learning for Strategy Learning:** Implement reinforcement learning to learn effective feature transformation strategies.\n- **Evaluation Metrics:** Use metrics like 1-RAE and F1-score to evaluate the performance of the proposed method.\n\n#### Expected Outcomes\nThe expected outcomes of this research include:\n- A stable, strategy-learning feature transformation method that reduces reliance on manual intervention.\n- Enhanced performance of downstream models by generating high-quality feature spaces.\n- Improved efficiency and accessibility of the data preparation phase in ML.\n\n#### Conclusion\nThis research aims to advance the field of machine learning by providing a robust solution to the critical challenge of automated feature transformation. By integrating graph-based methods with reinforcement learning, we propose a novel approach that addresses the limitations of existing methodologies and contributes to the development of more efficient and accessible ML systems.\n\n---\n\n### Next Steps\n1. **Peer Review:** Share the draft with peers or mentors for feedback.\n2. **Final Review and Submission:** Conduct a final review to ensure all aspects of the proposal are addressed and prepare it for submission to a relevant conference or journal.\n\nThis draft provides a 